Siobhan is a 30-year veteran of the board game and computer game industries. Her career began at Steve Jackson Games as editor of the Car Wars line. Moving to computer games, she joined legendary publisher Origin Systems, directing the award-winning Wing Commander II. After working as game developer and technology evangelist at The 3DO Company, Siobhan co-founded Illusion Machines Incorporated, an independent game studio in Austin, Texas, that developed games and applications for Microsoft, Virgin Interactive, MSN, and MicroProse.

Siobhan returned to Origin/Electronic Arts in 2000 as Director of Online Technology. Joining Microsoft as a Lead Developer for server development, security, and billing systems, she later became a Lead Program Manager, creating a peer-to-peer gaming platform for MSN Instant Messenger and leading development for the prototyping team that launched the Xbox Kinect project. Later, she joined The Amazing Society/Gazillion as Lead Server Engineer for the Marvel Super Hero Squad massively-multiplayer online game.

Siobhan is now Principal Engineer for Educational Technology at DigiPen Institute of Technology, guiding the development of administrative tools and educational resources across the campus. She also serves as Senior Lecturer, teaching networking, computer security, concurrent programming, and software engineering.

Once upon a time, back in the days of minicomputers and pteranodons, I was an operating system programmer and chip designer. I wandered into application programming, got a teaching credential in computer science, and wrote code in Pascal, FORTRAN, PL/1, APL, C, various assembly languages, bash, assorted BASICs, and their ilk. I wandered away from designing & writing code for a living and worked on other things.

Eventually, I came back, focusing this time on HTML, CSS, perl, PHP, mySQL, and most recently Python. I'm not doing it for a living these days, and I feel a couple of decades out of date, but I'm having fun with it.

At the moment, I'm creating a point of sale system for my tea shop and designing some interactive exhibits using Raspberry Pi 3's at a wildlife sanctuary.
